      "message": "\u003e Just curious about the \"no packed\" structs.\n\n\u003e Because I\u0027m imagining that \"packing/unpacking\" data\n\u003e from non-packed structs to the serialised bytes will use some processing that\n\u003e would be \"free\" for the packed case (well, accessing them on the packed\n\u003e structs would have its own costs - are these big enough to justify the extra\n\u003e work on serialisation?).\n\nSo there\u0027s a bit to unpack (heh) in response here.\n\nI think there are a few motivations that drive the existence of a library:\n\n- Code reuse avoiding reimplementation\n- By the way of reuse, a singular place for problems to be solved\n\nTaken together, with helpful design we can avoid having to fix one conceptual\nproblem in N library consumers.\n\nIf we\u0027re going to have a library, then we also should consider design and\nimplementation philosophies. From experience I think some key concerns are that\nit provides users with:\n\n1. An ergonomic interface, that is\n2. Safe to use\n\nConversely, we wish to avoid forcing users into performing rituals that are\ntedious and/or error-prone.\n\nI\u0027ll argue that packed structs don\u0027t meet either the motivations or the\nphilosophical concerns.\n\nExposing packed structs in the API suggests to users that it\u0027s reasonable to\ncast message buffers to the type and move on. This is not safe or ergonomic\nbecause:\n\n1. It moves the security boundary of message handling to the user\n2. It constrains how the user can make use of the structs\n3. It moves the concern of endian-correctness to the user\n4. It doesn\u0027t account for the DMTF specifying PLDM message encodings that cannot\n   be represented by C structs\n\nRegarding the first point, with packed structs every user must now test\nthe length of the underlying buffer and the length of the valid data in the\nunderlying buffer against the size of the struct before the cast. Failing to do\nso exposes the user to security problems through undefined behaviour. This isn\u0027t\nsafe. The test suite already made this mistake quite a bit:\n\nhttps://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/libpldm/+/90475\n\nRegarding the second point, forming a pointer or reference to an inappropriately\naligned object yields undefined behaviour (e.g. C23 (N3220), J.2, (24)). Correct\nuse requires users extract data from struct members into appropriately aligned\nstorage before taking a pointer or reference. This is not ergonomic - these\nwork-arounds are tedious. Further, exactly which struct member object is located\nin unaligned storage depends on the base address of the storage underlying the\nstruct, which makes simple approaches error-prone.\n\nAgain, the test suite already fell into this trap quite a bit. In the case\nof C++ we have the added bonus that the fact that a reference is taken is not\nnecessarily clear at the call-site:\n\nhttps://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/libpldm/+/90476\n\nReturning to the list, I think the third point above is relatively\nstraight-forward - the user now needs to apply the usual endian-conversion\nAPIs themselves, for each struct member referenced. Again, this is tedious and\nerror-prone. It\u0027s easy to forget. It\u0027s not clear whether the struct object you\nhave in hand has itself been subject to endian conversion, which may lead to\ndouble-conversions from the confusion. Where structs contain members that\ncapture the length of associated buffers, failure to perform accurate endian\nhandling can result in invalid buffer accesses with the usual consequences.\n\nIn the end the need to apply endian-conversions requires that we copy all\nthe data anyway, so the packed-struct strategy doesn\u0027t gain us anything\nperformance-wise, and we still have all the downsides.\n\nI\u0027ve previously made the argument for why the library should handle endian\nconversions here:\n\nhttps://amboar.github.io/notes/2023/06/19/representations-and-design-boundaries-with-endianness.html\n\nAs for the fourth point, see the \"rangeFieldFormat\" and associated members\ndefined in DSP0248 v1.3.0, 28.4 Numeric Sensor PDR, Table 79. We have to follow\nthe process to extract the members because a C union expressly does not have the\nnecessary behaviour.\n\nSo, instead, the libpldm API design principle is that we provide\nmessage-handling APIs that take responsibility for security, correctness, and\nergonomics, and to do this in a way that is also free of IO and allocations.\n\nTo that end, we follow the the principle that the APIs either:\n\n1. Take a message struct then encode it to a message buffer or produce an error, or,\n2. Take a message buffer then decode it to a message struct or produce an error.\n\nWe require that:\n\n- The structs are not packed to remove the ergonomic problems around alignment\n\n- The message structs always contain values in host-endianness - all endian\n  conversion is performed in the library, eliminating opportunities for failure\n  or confusion.\n\n- The security boundary for the message handling is then in the library, as all\n  necessary length checks are embedded there. If the API call indicates success\n  then the result can be trusted.\n\nRegarding the last point, some work has been done to make the library\u0027s\nimplementation of this guarantee ergonomic. This is the motivation for the\nmsgbuf APIs that we ask are used in new contributions. The msgbuf API design\nprinciple is that appropriate length checks are _always_ performed, and compiler\noptimisations remove those it can prove are unnecessary. Put another way,\nfailing to insert an absolute length check becomes a missed optimisation rather\nthan a security failure.\n\nI think that together, these justify the extra work.\n\n\u003e Indeed, there are other packed structs on the same header - will they also\n\u003e be deprecated?\n\nIdeally yes, but I can\u0027t spend all my time doing so. Hopefully we can make\nincremental progress.",
